{{refimprove|date=June 2010}} {{Infobox person | name = Bill Aucoin | image = Bill Aucoin 2008.jpg | alt = | caption = Bill Aucoin, 2008 | birthname = William Martin Aucoin | birth_date = {{Birth date|1943|12|29}} | birth_place = [[Ayer, Massachusetts]], U.S. | death_date = {{Death date and age|2010|06|28|1943|12|29}} | death_place = [[Aventura, Florida]], U.S. | nationality = American | partner = Roman Fernandez | occupation = Band manager }}
'''William Martin Aucoin''' (December 29, 1943 – June 28, 2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/77343/kiss-manager-bill-aucoin-dies?ref=rss|title=KISS Manager Bill Aucoin Dies|website=Allaccess.com|accessdate=20 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100628/ap_en_ot/us_obit_aucoin|title=Aucoin, manager who discovered Kiss, dies at 66 - Yahoo! News|date=2 July 2010|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=20 August 2017|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100702023352/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20100628/ap_en_ot/us_obit_aucoin|archivedate=2 July 2010|df=}}</ref> was an American band manager, well known for his work with the rock band [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]].
==Biography== {{moresources|section|date=August 2017}} Born in 1943 in Ayer, Massachusetts, Aucoin attended [[Northeastern University]] and graduated with a degree in film.<ref name="aucoin.biz">{{cite web |url=http://www.aucoin.biz/au_pages/about.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704124202/http://www.aucoin.biz/au_pages/about.php |archivedate=2010-07-04 |df= }} </ref> He worked at [[WGBH-TV|WGBH]] in [[Boston]] during his college years and after. Aucoin later worked at Teletape Productions as a cinematographer.<ref name="aucoin.biz"/> Credited with discovering [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]], Aucoin managed the group for nearly a decade. He was fired in 1982 due to a dispute about the band's appearance plus his drug abuse,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/02/23/business/the-bad-boys-start-watching-their-pockets.html?pagewanted=all|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|title=The Bad Boys Start Watching Their Pockets|first=Geraldine|last=Fabrikant|date=1997-02-23|accessdate=2010-04-26}}</ref> but later worked with the band on various [[DVD]] projects.
Aucoin produced a television show called ''[[Supermarket Sweep]]'' in the early 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1568719/|title=Bill Aucoin|website=IMDb|accessdate=20 August 2017}}</ref> From 2005 to 2007, Aucoin went into the Broadway business with a staging of [[The Who]]'s ''[[Quadrophenia (musical)|Quadrophenia]]'', which showed intermittently for two years in [[Anaheim]] and [[Los Angeles]].
Aucoin had reentered the management business with his company Aucoin Globe Entertainment, at the time of his death of surgical complications from [[prostate cancer]]. He was survived by partner Roman Fernandez and sisters Betty Britton and Janet Bankowski. A statement from [[Paul Stanley]] and [[Gene Simmons]] described him as "our irreplaceable original manager, mentor and dear friend… Words cannot convey his impact on us or those close to him."<ref>Ling, Dave, "The Dirt: Bill Aucoin"; ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' #148, August 2010, p20</ref>
