'''Craig R. Benson''' (born October 8, 1954<ref name="NGA">[http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_new_hampshire/col2-content/main-content-list/title_benson_craig.html New Hampshire Governor Craig Benson]. [[National Governors Association]]. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.{{cite web|url=http://www.nga.org/portal/site/nga/menuitem.29fab9fb4add37305ddcbeeb501010a0/?vgnextoid=bd18224971c81010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD&vgnextchannel=e449a0ca9e3f1010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-02-06 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629134820/http://www.nga.org/portal/site/nga/menuitem.29fab9fb4add37305ddcbeeb501010a0/?vgnextoid=bd18224971c81010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD&vgnextchannel=e449a0ca9e3f1010VgnVCM1000001a01010aRCRD |archivedate=June 29, 2011 |df=mdy }} </ref>) is an American politician and entrepreneur who served as the 79th [[Governor of New Hampshire]] from 2003 to 2005.  Benson first came to public attention when he founded [[Cabletron Systems]], now known as [[Enterasys Networks]], which became one of the largest employers in [[New Hampshire]].

== Early life and business career ==
Benson attended [[Chatham High School (New Jersey)|Chatham High School]] in [[Chatham, New Jersey]]. After receiving a [[bachelor's degree]] in finance from [[Babson College]] in 1977, Benson attended [[Syracuse University]], graduating with an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] in 1979.<ref name="NGA"/>

In 1983, Benson and partner Robert Levine started [[Cabletron Systems]] in Levine's garage.<ref name="NYTimes1">Fisher, Lawrence M. (August 7, 1997). "[https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/07/business/cabletron-s-chief-executive-plans-to-step-down-sept-1.html?src=pm Cabletron's Chief Executive Plans to Step Down Sept. 1]". ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref> The company moved to [[Rochester, New Hampshire]] in 1985 and went public in 1989, with what was then the largest [[Initial public offering|IPO]] in [[Wall Street]] history.<ref>Viscarolasaga, Efrain (June 20, 2005). "[http://www.masshightech.com/stories/2005/06/20/story12-Enterasys-closes-Rochester-NH-facility-to-consolidate-operations-in-Andover.html Enterasys closes Rochester, N.H., facility to consolidate operations in Andover] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402212325/http://www.masshightech.com/stories/2005/06/20/story12-Enterasys-closes-Rochester-NH-facility-to-consolidate-operations-in-Andover.html |date=April 2, 2012 }}". MassHighTech.com. Retrieved on February 6, 2011. </ref> In 1991, Benson was named "Entrepreneur of the Year" by ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc. Magazine]]''.<ref>Hyatt, Joshua (January 1, 2001). "[http://www.inc.com/magazine/19910101/4408.html Born to Run]". ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]'' Retrieved on February 6, 2011. {{dead link|date=August 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

The company grew to have over $1.8&nbsp;billion in annual revenue, but over time Cabletron began to face heavy competition in the industry.<ref name="NYTimes2">"[https://www.nytimes.com/1999/06/05/business/a-cabletron-systems-founder-steps-down.html?src=pm A Cabletron Systems Founder Steps Down]". ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 5, 1999. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref> Benson resigned in 1999,<ref name="NYTimes2"/> and Cabletron was dissolved into four separate companies ([[Enterasys Networks]], [[Aprisma Management Technologies]], [[Riverstone Networks]], and [[Global Network Technology Services]]) in January 2000.<ref name="Indus">Kelly, Matt (March 1, 2002). "[http://www.indusbusinessjournal.com/ME2/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications::Article&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&tier=4&id=2550A15959924553B6E7D0EA4DF3CD8D After splitting up Cabletron, Piyush Patel mulls his future]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309172827/http://www.indusbusinessjournal.com/ME2/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications%3A%3AArticle&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&tier=4&id=2550A15959924553B6E7D0EA4DF3CD8D |date=March 9, 2012 }}". Indusbusinessjournal.com. Retrieved on February 6, 2011. </ref> The company's fragmentation brought layoffs,<ref name="Network">Hohman, Robin (December 22, 1997). "[https://books.google.com/books?id=lRsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA6&lpg=PA6&dq=&source=bl&ots=3ejyHDOSeD&sig=ClP6oeisHB0MszwizJ7upFIBmMc&hl=en&ei=fCtPTZmmCYKB8gbd19nxDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false Cabletron cuts rile customers]". ''[[Network World]]'', p. 6. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref> declines in stock price,<ref name="Indus"/> and shareholder lawsuits.<ref>[[Enterasys Networks]] (January 18, 2005). "[http://www.enterasys.com/company/press-release-item.aspx?id=562 Enterasys Networks Agrees to Settle Shareholder Suit Against Its Predecessor, Cabletron Systems]". Press Release. Retrieved on February 6, 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625020327/http://www.enterasys.com/company/press-release-item.aspx?id=562 |date=June 25, 2013 }}</ref>

== Governor of New Hampshire ==
Benson began running for governor of New Hampshire in 2001, promising to use technology and greater efficiency to save money in state government. Political signs appeared across the Granite State proclaiming "This is Benson Country." He was elected governor on November 5, 2002, in an open race to succeed the retiring governor, [[Jeanne Shaheen]]. In the [[political primary|primaries]], Benson spent more than $15&nbsp;million—$11&nbsp;million of it his own money<ref>Steen, p. 20.</ref>—in an effort to defeat former State Senator [[Bruce Keough]] and former [[United States Senator|U.S. Senator]] [[Gordon Humphrey]] to win the Republican nomination, making Benson's victory one of the most expensive in American history.<ref>McDonald, Greg (September 13, 2002). "[http://www.stateline.org/live/ViewPage.action?siteNodeId=136&languageId=1&contentId=14960 McBride Claims Victory in Florida Dem Primary]". Stateline.org. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref> In the general election, Benson overwhelmingly defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] state Senator [[Mark Fernald]], 59 percent to 38 percent.<ref>Steen, p. 19.</ref> Benson successfully made Fernald's support for a statewide income tax the dominant issue in the race. Benson spent more than $9&nbsp;million, again mostly his own money, in this race.<ref>"[http://articles.cnn.com/2002-11-05/politics/elec02.nh.g.hotrace_1_income-tax-craig-benson-sales-tax?_s=PM:ALLPOLITICS Benson projected to win N.H. governor race]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005004100/http://articles.cnn.com/2002-11-05/politics/elec02.nh.g.hotrace_1_income-tax-craig-benson-sales-tax?_s=PM%3AALLPOLITICS |date=October 5, 2012 }}". [[CNN]], November 5, 2002. Retrieved on February 6, 2011. </ref>

As Governor, Benson pushed for state agencies to institute across-the-board budget reductions, and used a custom made, extra large "VETO" stamp to reject a state budget he thought was too large.<ref name="NHPR">Rogers, Josh (June 30, 2003). "[http://www.nhpr.org/node/4925 Lawmakers, Benson Prepare For Override Vote]". [[New Hampshire Public Radio]]. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref> Benson also signed into law a bill that required [[parental notification]] for minors seeking an abortion;<ref>Zezima, Katie (June 21, 2003). "[https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/21/us/national-briefing-new-england-new-hampshire-law-requires-parents-consent-for.html?src=pm National Briefing | New England: New Hampshire: Law Requires Parents' Consent For Some Abortions]". ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref>  this law was later challenged and upheld in the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in the case ''[[Ayotte v. Planned Parenthood of New England]]'', but subsequently repealed by the New Hampshire legislature in 2007.<ref>Vestal, Christine (June 22, 2006). "[http://www.stateline.org/live/printable/story?contentId=121780 States probe limits of abortion policy]." Stateline.org. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref>

Benson's administration came under criticism following the resignation of [[Attorney General]] [[Peter Heed]], who had been accused of sexual harassment. While an investigation cleared Heed of any wrongdoing, it revealed improper interference by Benson's security commissioner.<ref>Schweitzer, Sarah (October 26, 2004). "[http://www.boston.com/news/local/new_hampshire/articles/2004/10/26/nhs_race_for_governor_spotlights_scandals/ N.H.'s race for governor spotlights scandals]". ''[[The Boston Globe]]''. Retrieved on February 6, 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103045007/http://www.boston.com/news/local/new_hampshire/articles/2004/10/26/nhs_race_for_governor_spotlights_scandals/ |date=November 3, 2012 }}</ref>  Further criticism stems from the inappropriate awarding of a nearly $900,000 [[no-bid contract]] by his "volunteer" adviser (and former Cabletron human resource administrator) Linda Pepin,<ref>Barrick, Daniel (January 16, 2005). "[https://archive.is/20120723080644/http://www.concordmonitor.com/article/lynch-council-want-contract-competition Lynch, council want contract competition]". ''[[Concord Monitor]]''. Retrieved on 201102-06.</ref> who was not licensed to broker such a deal.<ref>Smith, Ashley (October 20, 2010). "[http://www.thelobbynh.com/news/885346-382/day-2-nhs-top-20-political-scandals.html Day 2: NH’s Top 20 Political Scandals]" ''(cached version)'', #14. Thelobbynh.com. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref>

Benson also frequently used "volunteers" in his office to do gubernatorial work, but would not say who they were or what they did.<ref>Barrick, Daniel (February 2, 2005). "[https://archive.is/20120724072645/http://www.concordmonitor.com/article/lynch-staff-disclose-finances Lynch, staff disclose finances]". ''[[Concord Monitor]]''. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref> These were not volunteers in the sense that they were unpaid staffers volunteering their time, rather Benson paid their salaries out of his own pocket, making them volunteers in the sense that they did not draw state salaries. This move was controversial, while proponents noted that Benson was generously allowing the state to save money, critics were concerned that it would limit scrutiny of the volunteer staff. Reporters discovered that one of these "volunteers" (and former Cabletron director of operations), Angela Blaisdell, was New Hampshire's official liaison with the federal government on [[homeland security]].<ref>Rogers, Josh (December 9, 2003). "[http://www5.nhpr.org/taxonomy/term/6971 AG: Benson Volunteers are State Officials]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}". [[New Hampshire Public Radio]]. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref> In addition, Benson was accused of engaging in political payback when Dori Wiggin, supervisor of the Department of Environmental Services Wetlands Division in [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire|Portsmouth]], was transferred to the department's [[Concord, New Hampshire|Concord]] headquarters. Under Wiggin, the DES had fined Benson in 1998 and 2003 for excavating beach sand without a permit at his [[Rye, New Hampshire|Rye]] oceanfront home.<ref>Goldstein, Meredith; David Rattigan & Clare Kittredge (April 15, 2004). "[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/618419011.html?FMT=ABS&date=Apr+15,+2004 Healthy Landscapes Seminar]". ''[[Boston Globe]]''. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref>

Benson was also criticized, by both supporters and critics, for a management style that was considered "autocratic".<ref name="Defeated">Schweitzer, Sarah (November 4, 2004). "[http://www.boston.com/news/politics/governors/articles/2004/11/04/defeated_after_1_term_nh_governor_fades_out/ Defeated after 1 term, N.H. governor fades out]". ''[[The Boston Globe]]''. Retrieved on February 6, 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130628004021/http://www.boston.com/news/politics/governors/articles/2004/11/04/defeated_after_1_term_nh_governor_fades_out/ |date=June 28, 2013 }}</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'', Benson stated that one of his first acts after being elected was to purchase a large, high table at which to hold his meetings. Those in attendance were to stand during meetings, and any latecomers were locked out. "It's to remind people we're here to get in and do our business and get out," he explained.<ref>Rosenbaum, David E. (August 8, 2004). "[https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/08/us/2004-campaign-new-hampshire-governor-businessman-with-businesslike-plan.html?src=pm THe 2004 Campaign: The New Hampshire Governor; A Businessman With a Businesslike Plan]". ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved on February 6, 2011.</ref>

In the 2004 election, Benson lost to Democratic challenger [[John H. Lynch|John Lynch]]—only the second time in 78 years that an incumbent New Hampshire governor was denied a second term—in a very close race, with Lynch securing just 51% of the vote.<ref name="Defeated"/>

== Personal life ==
Benson resides in [[Rye, New Hampshire]] with his wife Denise. They have two daughters.

Benson serves as an adjunct lecturer at [[Babson College]], his alma mater. In 1995, he was inducted into the college's Academy of Distinguished Entrepreneurs.<ref>[http://www3.babson.edu/academics/faculty/cbenson.cfm Faculty Profile: Craig R. Benson]. Babson College. Retrieved on February 6, 2011. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515013302/http://www3.babson.edu/academics/faculty/cbenson.cfm |date=May 15, 2011 }}</ref>

